rComments: The best professor for calculus 1

Very into the material but not super organized. Refused to give us questions for homework, had us buy a textbook and two modules and then ended up using photocopies of another textbook,  his questions on assignments and exams were unclear and/or had typos at your expense, very hard marker. I was interested in the material, but will avoid him later.

An excellent professor. Don't miss his classes or you won't pass. Gives difficult assignments but are totally worth the time. Explains in a fun and easy way. Helps students outside class. Very friendly and sweet. I would definitely take a class again with this professor.

Great prof! The homework can be long but it prepares you well for the tests. He's also very willing to help during and outside of class and really wants everyone to understand completely. Would definitely take a class with him again!
He is a WONDERFUL prof! One of the best maths teacher that I never had in my life.
He always wants to help students and encourage them to study well. I love attending class.
He is the best prof I've had so far! He makes the material very interesting and easy to understand. I absolutely loved going to class.
He is very precise and helpful.

Professor Bardestani is one of the best teachers I have ever had at the university of Ottawa.  Before taking this class, I did not like math courses at all, but his teaching style convinced me that math could be fun.  He is well-prepared, and always encourages students to engage in the class.
Excellent professor!

Really nice guy, friendly, but not a great prof for a computational course; assumed complicated topics were easy, didn't explain procedures correctly. Very poor timing throughout semester. Spent first two weeks discussing material that wasn't tested, and crammed half the exam material into the final three weeks. Entertaining lectures, unique/fun

Was a very dedicated prof, he made sure, to the best of his ability, that everybody understood the material conveyed. With that being said he wasn't afraid to challenge us and really make us delve into the concepts. However at the end of the day he was the kind of professor where you had nothing left to ask.

Professor means well, yet he makes the material more confusing and his tests are difficult. the good thing about him was that he always asked if we understand or not. The one thing I wasn't fond of is the way he added very important topics on the last week of lectures.

Fairly good prof. Enthusiastic and helpful, but not great at explaining things. The textbook is very good though - but Stewart's Multivariable Calculus works just as well. He started class saying he would focus on theoretical proofs but then actually focused on more problem-solving. He has a habit of wearing only 3 shirts (all math-themed). Young.
teacherRatingTags: ['Get ready to read', 'Lots of homework', 'Lecture heavy']

rComments: Professor is very confusing when  teaching. As for grading, the questions weren't fair. The topics we spent a lot of time on had the least points, whereas the topics we quickly went through had significant weight. Final exam, same story.

Omg, I've take another course I liked with him before, but this one is totally a disaster! Even if I already got an A on mat2322 (because I switched program, so I have to take mat2122), he is so CONFUSING! And he finished up the materials that was supposed to take 1month in 2weeks. DO NOT TAKE HIS MULTI CALC

This dude is hilarious. First assignment was hard, the rest were straightforward. Don't take his section if you aren't comfortable with writing a proof or two. Even if it isn't a "proof course", there will be a few.  He's super into the theory, you can tell he wants to talk about it. Also, super nice guy, he wants every single person to do well
Does not know how to teach.
If you like someone that will stand in front of the class and scream very broken english to you, this guy is your guy

He is very good at heart and knows the stuff too well. Always be attentive in the class and ask doubts. Lecture will be a bit hard to concentrate but if you do homework and make use of his office hours this should be an easy going course for you.

Doing suggested practice problems from the book is essential if you want a good grade. Lectures generally good, sometimes feel disorganized. Prof always available after classoffice to clarify material - use this time. Despite lack of clarity at times, prof actually wants you to do well and will try explaining material in different ways.

He comes off as mean at first, but if you pay attention, he just wants to make sure everyone is following along in class. He offers a lot of extra credit (you will have to remind him before he applies it) and assignments closely follow the notes. SIDE NOTE! He sounds like he's yelling at the class, but he just talks that way.
Full of empty promises. Don't trust anything he says, he's too forgetful and all over the place. Easy class but he can't teach

Material is fascinating. However the professor is too slow and places too much emphasis on some topics and spends too much time explaining some things that we fell behind by far. Exams are a memory test from assignments. Professor is good at teaching, just not at making exams. At all.

He remembers EVERY student, so don't skip too many classes. Take notes on lectures and do the assignments then you shouldn't have any problems taking exams. No Facebook connections in class. Although he often changes his mind about things, it shouldn't be too hard to get a good final grade.

Go to class, ask questions and hard work will get you a good grade. Don't hope to get any help  outside of class, or get any questions answered by emails.  Don't listen to his promising words of "answering emails" or "having extra office hours" ever. Half of the time he will forget what he said.

He expects students to be active in class. So, he gives extra points and he prohibits smartphone distractions.  The assignments are fairly from what you've been through in lectures. Work on it, and you'll get good grades.
This course is difficult, but if you put in the work, you should be able to get a good grade. He cares about his students and will you give you bonus points if you participate in class.

An excellent speaker, really funny, and he is willing to put in the hours to help you. However, he was quite difficult in the beginning, but I personally got used to this, and subsequently his second midterm and final exam were straightforward and easy. It was almost a shame to put in so much work and get easy exams. Assignments are really fun.

He's a nice guy but he doesn't really know how to teach. If you have a question he will help you out in office hours. He tries to be a good prof by the doesn't really know how to explain very well. He does care though.

Pretty much yells the whole class for student to answer his questions and expects you to know the subject without explaning it very well. Course itself isn't too bad but he doesn't create the best learning environment.
he doesn't explain very well and will yell until student answers. He is not organized. The man can't teach. But he will help you out if you go to his office hours. A nice guy but doesn't teach well

I love math, hated the class taught by this prof. He didn't talk loud, wrote very tiny on the board, and I found him to be very arrogant towards students. Didn't seem like he wanted to help anyone at all.

Good Prof. Always there to help if you dont understand something. He does call out people randomly to answer questions and participate which can be stressful if you dont like speaking out in class. Assignments can be tricky but exams are pretty easy.

Very good teacher, explains concepts well and makes sure you understand them before moving on. He HATES cell phones or any distractions in class so beware. He also likes to call on people randomly throughout the lecture to make sure you're understanding. His midterms and final are pretty easy and his assignments are fine.
